<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-456-983  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 456 983.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Oct 1 1990 v7 n39 p1(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>3.1 with TrueType now due next year. (Windows role defined;upgrade pushed back) (Apple and Microsoft Corp.'s TrueTypecomputer font software)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sherer, Paul M.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Apple Computer Corp and Microsoft Corp are developing a printerfont software package called TrueType to go with the enhancedversion of Microsoft Windows graphical user interface (GUI).andO;Windows 3.1's release, however, is being delayed from the end of1990 to the 1st or 2nd qtr of 1991 because of difficulties infinalizing the TrueType product.andP;  TrueType is supposed to enableusers to change fonts on-screen in a WYSIWYG Windows environment.andO;Microsoft is cancelling several scheduled demonstrations ofTrueType because it is not ready.andP;  Meanwhile, Microsoft isproceeding with the development and 1st qtr 1991 release of newdevice drivers to provide access to TrueType fonts from Windows3.0.andP;  The software publisher is also improving the Windows FileManager for Windows 3.1, since it is one of the more criticizedareas of the GUI.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (product development)Apple Computer Inc. (product development).andO;Ticker:    MSFT; AAPL.andO;Product:   Microsoft Windows 3.1 (Graphical user interface) (productdevelopment)Truetype (Computer font) (product development).andO;Topic:     Product DelayGraphical User InterfaceEnhancementsFonts.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>3.1 with TrueType Now Due Next YearandM;Microsoft Corp. has pushed back its target release date for Windows 3.1 untilthe first or second quarter of next year because of snags in developing itsTrueType outline-font technology, sources close to the company said lastweek.andM;Windows 3.1, originally planned for release by the end of this year, willinclude the TrueType font technology that Microsoft is developing with AppleComputer Inc., as well as an enhanced File Manager and several minor bugfixes.andP;  TrueType is designed to provide WYSIWYG capabilities and let usersmanipulate fonts on-screen.andM;Although Microsoft has never formally announced Windows 3.1, officials havesaid the company planned to provide TrueType fonts in Windows 3.1 by the endof the year.andM;While not committing to a release date, Microsoft officials last weekacknowledged that they will not deliver Windows 3.1 with TrueType until thefirst quarter of 1991, and they confirmed their plans to improve theperformance of the Windows File Manager.andM;&quot;If you think that performance of File Manager is an issue, you'll enjoy thenext release,&quot; said Russ Werner, general manager of system marketing at theRedmond, Wash., firm.andM;Also in next year's first quarter, but before 3.1 is released, Microsofthopes to deliver a set of device driver disks that will give Windows 3.0users access to TrueType fonts, Werner said.andM;However, several Windows developers were skeptical of Microsoft'sfirst-quarter target for the Windows 3.1 release, saying that delivery of thenew version could be as far off as the end of the second quarter.andM;Microsoft has canceled its plans for a TrueType promotional blitz at thisweek's Seybold Desktop Publishing Conference, sources said.andM;&quot;It would be too embarrassing for Microsoft to make a big splash for TrueTypebut not be able to show it or announce [a release date],&quot; said a source whois familiar with Microsoft's plans.andM;Werner last week also confirmed that Microsoft has canceled a booth at theSeybold show and that no software vendors will demonstrate TrueType, addingthat TrueType will only be shown if Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates makes it apart of his key-note speech.andO;</TEXT></DOC>